assessment_details.task_description:
You will join a group of 3 or 4 people to conduct a case study of a business enterprise and write a case report. You will choose a company, collect relevant quantitative and qualitative information about the company, its industry and institutional backgrounds based on which to describe the company’s ownership and organizational structures, internal governance mechanisms including corporate culture, codes of conduct, managerial delegation, incentive, monitoring, and balance of power, relations with key stakeholders such as governments, suppliers and customers, investment and financing decisions, and so on. Then, you will identify and analyze a set of questions based on the information you have gathered, provide the root causes and recommendations.

Finally, it is expected that all group members contribute equally to the task. Students will be required to complete a peer assessment of their group members. The results of this peer assessment may impact the final individual result of students. This peer assessment will be due 1 week after the final submission date.

The structure and content of the written case report include:

Situation : an opening paragraph describing problem(s) faced by the company, and decisions to be made;

Background : to the extent relevant, using several paragraphs to describe the company’s businesses, owners, managers, history and landmark events, key stakeholders, market and regulatory environments, performance relative to peer firms, and so on;

Analysis : focusing on the company’s problems, using several paragraphs or sub-sections to describe the constraints (intermediate and root causes) resulting in the problems and supporting quantitative and qualitative evidence;

Recommendation : using several paragraphs (sub-sections) to perform cost and benefit analysis and suggest changes in the company’s structures and associated decisions that mitigate the identified problems, such as business combination, ownership, organization, finance, and/or governance.

Case report document requirements:

The written report should have a cover page stating the title, date, contributing members’ names, and an executive summary stating the objectives and outcomes of the report. The report should be submitted as a MS Word file, Times New Roman font, title size 14 points, text size 12 points, line space 1.5, page number at the bottom-center, footnotes, figures and tables clearly numbered and titled, located near corresponding text descriptions if not on the same page, quoting the number of each footnote, figure, and table in the text, quoting sources of information in the text, and listing all the sources in a list of references at the end of the report. The total report should not exceed 20 pages including the cover page, the text, and the references. Augmented information such as sample and data descriptions, variable definitions, list of peer firms, scenario analysis should be included as appendix tables attached to the report.

You will write an independent research proposal on a research question that you have identified from your previous group-based case study. Your focal research question should be different and clearly distinguishable from those of your peer study group members, but you could benefit from the insights of their analyses. In the proposal you should state the research question, describe its real-life and theoretical relevance, apply economic analysis you have learned from the course to identify key factors in answering the questions, whether these factors and their effects are consistent with the case study findings, and develop hypotheses and empirical strategy if you were going to test them on a large sample.

Structure and content of the research proposal:

One paragraph to state the research question , its relevance in theory and reality;

Several paragraphs to introduce institutional background and relevant literature ;

Several paragraphs in several sub-sections to identifying key constraining factors and analyzing their effects on outcomes, guided by relevant economic theories learned from this course, and state the hypotheses ;

Several paragraphs in several sub-sections to describe empirical design and strategy, including data sources, sample selection procedure, estimation models, variable construction, and statistical methods, and empirical approaches to address potential issues such as alternative hypotheses, data and/or sampling biases, omitted variable and reversed causality problems.

One paragraph to summarize expected results of the research, compare the expected results with those found the real-life case study, how the research will advance the literature, and caveat of the research.

Note that execution of the empirical analysis is not necessary . However, subject to data and time availability, to motivate your research, you could employ relevant and handy data to illustrate the key pattern or relation in a figure.

Research proposal document requirements:

The written proposal should have a title page presenting the title, date, your name and an abstract stating the objective, the questions, the relevance, and expected outcomes of the research. The proposal should be submitted as a MS Word file, Times New Roman font, title size 14 points, text size 12 points, line space 1.5, page number at the bottom-center, footnotes, figures and tables clearly numbered and titled, located near corresponding text descriptions if not on the same page, quoting the number of each footnote, figure, and table in the text, quoting sources of information in the text, and listing all the sources in a list of references at the end of the proposal. The total report should not exceed 15 pages including the title page, the text, tables and figures, and the references. Augmented information should be included as appendix tables attached to the proposal but not counted as the body of the proposal.
